Credit card Fraud Detection and investigation of various Data Imputation techniques¶

Overview¶

In this project we will be following the workflow for a machine learning project as defined in O'Reilly's Hands-on Machine Learning textbook:

  1. Frame the problem
  2. Get the data
  3. Explore the data
  4. Prepare the data
  5. Explore models
  6. Fine-tune models
  7. Present solution

1. Frame the problem¶

The goal of this project is to use a binary classifier to identify fraudulent transactions. The training data comes from a Kaggle competition that contains partially generated and partially real data.

For this project, we will be using ROC-AUC as our performance metric. ROC-AUC is a metric used specifically for binary classification models, and works by plotting an ROC curve, which is the True Positive rate against the False Positive rate at different thresholds, and then calculates the area under this curve. A perfect ROC-AUC score is therefore 1, and completely random (with balanced classes) would be 0.5 (higher is better). The reasons behind choosing this metric are:

  • ROC-AUC is insensitive to class balance, which is crucial for our data given that we have very few instances of fraudulent transactions
  • It provides a single number which makes it easy to compare model performance
  • Kaggle uses this performance metric, so it is easy to see how our preliminary models compare to other submissions

Although there is no missing data present in the training set, we will manually introduce them so we can investigate various Data Imputation methods.

We notice a few things. Most of the features are given generic names, so this doesn't give us any intuitive understanding of whether they may or may not be important for use to include in models. Some of the features are named, however, and contain more specific information about the transaction represented by each row. From Kaggle:

  • Time contains the seconds elapsed between each transaction and the first transaction in the dataset.

  • Amount is the transaction Amount

  • Class is the response variable and it takes value 1 in case of fraud and 0 otherwise.

We also learn from Kaggle that features V1, V2, … V28 are the principal components obtained with PCA, meaning that we may not need to do any dimensionality reduction on this data.

From this plot, we can see that Time and id are very highly correlated. This is because id appears to represent the index of the data, and Time represents the time in seconds elapsed between each transaction and the first transaction in the dataset. They therefore represent very similar information, and we can reasonably drop id from our model training. We also see strong correlation between Amount and V20, although since we do not know the context/meaning of V20, it is impossible to think of a reason behind why this is the case.

As we can see, all columns have no mising values

Remove the columns id and Class:

  • id refers to the index of the row, so makes no sense for there to be missing values, therefore we have no reason to test imputation methods on this column
  • Class is the response variable, so if there is missing data in this column, we would predict on this row instead of imputing the missing value

Remove a random selection of 10% of the data by randomly selecting row and column indices pairs, with each row and column having a 10% probability of being selected

In [ ]:
def removeVals (dataset, total_vals, percent_to_remove):
    dataset = dataset.copy()
    rows_to_remove = dataset.sample(frac = percent_to_remove, replace = True).index
    for i in rows_to_remove:
        column_to_remove = dataset.sample(n=1, axis=1).columns[0]
        dataset.loc[i, column_to_remove] = numpy.nan
    return dataset


imp_train = removeVals(imp_train, num_rows, 0.1*num_cols)

Simple imputation¶

The first method uses SciKit Learn's SimpleImputer, and we will use strategy = "median". This will replace the missing values with the median of the non-missing values in it's column. This will preserve the distribution of values as best as possible and is also one of the most common. Additionally, using the median rather than the mean is more robust to outliers. Finally, this method takes a trivial amount of time to run.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer

medianImputer = SimpleImputer(strategy = "median")
In [ ]:
# Get a list of the column names so we can re-label the data later
columns = imp_train_1.columns
imp_train_1 = medianImputer.fit_transform(imp_train_1)
imp_train_1 = pd.DataFrame(imp_train_1)
imp_train_1.columns = columns

We can use the RMSE of the imputed values vs the real values in order to assess the performance of the imputation method. This gives us a metric that describes the variance of the imputed value compared to the actual value, and gives an indication of how close our substitued values are to what they are supposed to be.

We can define a function to do this

In [ ]:
def calculateImputedRMSE(trueValues, imputedValues, mssingValues):
    selected_true = trueValues[mssingValues==True]
    selected_imputed = imputedValues[mssingValues==True]
    #calculate the RMSE between selected values
    rmse = numpy.sqrt(((selected_true - selected_imputed) ** 2).mean())
    return rmse

We can make a function to do this

In [ ]:
col_means = imp_train.mean().abs()

def printOverallMeans(RMSE_list):
    total = 0
    for i, mean in enumerate(col_means):
        total += RMSE_list[i]/mean
    print(f"{total/col_means.size}")

K-Nearest Neighbor Imputation¶

Next, we will try to use a K-Nearest Neighbors Imputation method, which takes advantage of the information contained within the dataframe a bit better than the simple median imputing method. K-Nearest Neighbors finds the K-Nearest Neighbors of the missing dataset using Euclidian Distance, and imputes the missing values using a Uniform average of these neighbors. We found in testing that increasing the number of neighbors does not have a significant effect on the RMSE of imputed vs actual values, however it leads to significantly increased computational time, so for this reason, we set n_neighbors = 2.

Combination Method¶

To see how good of an imputation method we can create, we now try to combine the best attributes of the KNN and Forward Fill methods seen above. KNN was the best for all feature types except for Time, and Forward Fill was nearly perfect for imputing missing Time Values. We can create a function ForwardNeighbor that will work in a SciKit Learn Pipeline, and then build such a pipeline that includes a KNN imputer, so that we only need to run one line of code each time we want to impute a new dataframe.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin

class ForwardNeighbour(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin) :

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self
    
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        X['Time'] = X['Time'].fillna(method='ffill')
        return X

Outlier Investigation¶

Firstly, we can try to remove outliers in our dataset, as some of the models we will attempt to train may be very sensitive to outliers.

def IQR_Outliers (X, features):

    print('# of features: ', len(features))
    print('Features: ', features)

    indices = [x for x in X.index]
    #print(indices)
    print('Number of samples: ', len(indices))
    
    out_indexlist = []
        
    for col in features:
       
        Q1 = np.quantile(X[col], 25.)
        Q3 = np.quantile(X[col], 75.)
        
        cut_off = (Q3 - Q1) * 1.5
        upper, lower = Q3 + cut_off, Q1 - cut_off
        print ('\nFeature: ', col)
        print ('Upper and Lower limits: ', upper, lower)
                
        outliers_index = X[col][(X[col] < lower) | (X[col] > upper)].index.tolist()
        outliers = X[col][(X[col] < lower) | (X[col] > upper)].values
        print('Number of outliers: ', len(outliers))
        #print('Outliers Index: ', outliers_index)
        #print('Outliers: ', outliers)
        
        out_indexlist.extend(outliers_index)
        
    #using set to remove duplicates
    out_indexlist = list(set(out_indexlist))
    out_indexlist.sort()
    print('\nNumber of rows with outliers: ', len(out_indexlist))
    #print('List of rows with outliers: ', out_indexlist)

We can define a pipeline to do this

In [ ]:
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer

# Custom Transformer that removes outliers from the dataset
class OutlierRemover(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, threshold=3): # z: Number of Standard deviations away from the mean to be considered
        self.threshold = threshold   # an outlier.
   
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self
   
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        X = X.copy()
        X = X[(numpy.abs(stats.zscore(X)) < self.threshold).all(axis=1)]
        return X


# Defining the pipeline: outlier remover
pipelineOutliers = Pipeline([
    ('outlier_remover', OutlierRemover()),
])

In [ ]:
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator
from sklearn.base import TransformerMixin

class DropColumns(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self 
    
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        X_new = X.drop(columns=['id'])
        X_new["Time"] = X_new["Time"].apply(lambda x: x / 3600 % 24)
        return X_new

We can make a pipeline for the cleaning

In [ ]:
pipelineMain = Pipeline([
    ('dropper', DropColumns()),
    ('standard_scalar', StandardScaler())
])

SMOTE approach¶

We can see that in the original dataset, there are very few instances of fraud. This will make training and model evaulation very challenging, as a model will return an accuracy of nearly 100% by simply predicting that all transactions are of Class = 0, i.e. not fraudulent. Therefore we will use Synthetic Minority Oversampling, which duplicates examples from the minority class, fraudulent transactions (Class = 1), in order to balance the class distribution. To do this, we use the SMOTEENN function from the imblearn package. This will combine the oversampling of minority classes and undersampling of majority classes, and clean the data using Edited Nearest Neighbors, which will remove samples from the majority class to match the minority class.

In [ ]:
#SMOTEENN approach
from imblearn.combine import SMOTEENN
x_train = pd.DataFrame(pipelineMain.fit_transform(x_train)) 

# SMOTEEN first oversamples the minority class using SMOTE, then cleans the data using ENN
smote_enn = SMOTEENN(random_state=0)
x_train, y_train = smote_enn.fit_resample(x_train, y_train)

5. Explore models¶

Now that the data has been cleaned, we can begin to train models.

SGD Classifier (Stochastic Gradient Descent)¶

We can start with an SGD classifier, as seen in lectures, to see what a solid benchmark looks like. SGD Classifiers are a good set of models to use as a benchmark, as they are very efficient and simple. We will also start by intially choosing accuracy as our performance measure. SMOTEENN rebalanced the data, so the benchmark, i.e. guessing by random chance, should be an accuracy and ROC-AUC of 50%.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import SGDClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score


class_counts = y_train.value_counts()
class_weights = dict(1/class_counts)
sgd_classifier = SGDClassifier(random_state = 42, class_weight=class_weights)
sgd_classifier.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Check Accuracy


cross_val_score(sgd_classifier, x_train, y_train, cv = 5, scoring = "roc_auc")
Out[ ]:
array([0.80644942, 0.80563043, 0.80691787, 0.80584543, 0.80755882])

This looks okay, although these scores are based on the training data so there could of been a case of overfitting. We may also want to see precision and recall scores and we can also plot a confusion matrix to visualise our results

We can make a function to do this, and this will work for later parts where we produce the probability and not the class

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_predict
from sklearn.metrics import recall_score
from sklearn.metrics import precision_score

def displayResults(y_train, predictions):
    labels = np.where(predictions >= 0.5, 1, 0)
    matrix = confusion_matrix(y_train, labels)

    sns.heatmap(matrix, annot=True, fmt='d')
    matplotlib.pyplot.show()

    print(f"Precision score of SGD classifier on train: {precision_score(y_train, labels)}")
    print(f"Recall score of SGD classifier on train: {recall_score(y_train, labels)}")
In [ ]:
y_train_predictions = cross_val_predict(sgd_classifier, x_train, y_train, cv=5)

We have correctly predicted 144,085 fraudulant cases and missed 30,843, which is okay. The classifier has also mistakenly identified 72,133 unfraudulent trasnactions as fraud

For a basic model this is okay, however it definitely can be improved

Lets see how it performs on the data we set aside from the training set to evaluate how the model performs on unseen data. This will also give us an indication as to whether this model is over- or under-fit

Decision tree classifier¶

Lets try using a decision tree classifier to see if we can potentially improve on this. A decision tree will provide a nice improvement to the interpretability of our model, although its natural tendency to be overfitted is something we will need to pay attention to in our evaluation.

In [ ]:

print(cross_val_score(tree_classifier, x_train, y_train, cv = 5, scoring = "roc_auc"))

6. Fine tune models¶

Our best model so far was our Random Forest Classifier.

We started with a reasonably good model, but we can now try to fine tune some of the parameters in order to see how good of a classifier we can get. We will first start by performing a grid search on the number of trees within our model, and the maximum depth of each tree.

To try and avoid overfitting, we will be using stratified K fold to keep the feature distributions proportional to the original dataset for each fold.

We will assess each model using the ROC_AUC score.

In [ ]:

    'n_estimators': [75, 50, 25],

    'ccp_alpha':[0.001],
}

We can also test how the ccp_alpha hyperparameter will affect our models. To do this, we will use a baseline model of 75 trees with a maximum depth of 30. We can try different levels of ccp_alpha and see how they go to preventing overfitting

To evaluate our final model it would be nice to see which features are most important

To do this we can use the built in model.feature_importances_ function, which calculates the mean reduction in impurity for each feature across all trees in the forest. This will give us a better indication as to which features contain the most explanatory power and tend to be towards the top (stump) of each tree.

In [ ]:
importances = final_model.feature_importances_

selected_cols = train.iloc[:, 1:-1]

selected_cols = train.copy().iloc[:, 1:-1].columns

indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]

for feature in range(x_train.shape[1]):
    print((f"{feature+1}, {selected_cols[indices[feature]]}: {importances[indices[feature]]}"))

Conclusion¶

The best model turned out to be the random forest with hyperparameters ccp_alpha = 0.002, max_depth = 40, and n_estimators = 75. The model can accurately identify a significant proportion of fraud cases, and while it may produce a relatively high number of false positives, the nature of fraud detection justifies a more cautious approach from the model. Additionally, it is best to utilize the combined imputation method if there were to be missing values in the data. This method produced the best performance of the imputation methods that we evaluated, and therefore is likely to be the least intrusive in terms of affecting results when filling in missing values.
